# Override GitHub Linguist's default detection so .a / .ap files render in
# the GitHub web UI. By default GitHub treats `.a` as a GNU ar archive
# (binary) and won't render it at all.
#
# linguist-detectable=false keeps these files out of the repo's "Languages"
# bar — this is a JavaScript project; the .a/.ap files are study material.
#
# GRAMMAR DECISION: an A/B/C/D/E comparison (each top-level folder forced to a
# different Linguist assembly grammar) found `asm` (Assembly, NASM grammar) the
# best fit for LCC, so it's now the global default for all .a/.ap files. LCC
# isn't a real ISA, so no stock grammar is perfect; `asm` just reads best for
# the surrounding scaffolding (comments, .directives, labels, register-name
# heuristics). For pixel-accurate LCC highlighting use the lcc-tools VS Code
# grammar (or feed that .tmLanguage to Shiki on a GitHub Pages docs site);
# GitHub.com itself has no per-repo custom-grammar hook.
#
# Linguist single-word aliases (attribute values can't contain spaces):
#   asm  = Assembly             (source.assembly, NASM grammar)  <-- chosen
#   gas  = Unix Assembly        (source.x86, GNU AS)
#   arm  = ARM Assembly         (source.asm.arm)
#   m68k = Motorola 68K Assembly(source.m68k)
#   LLVM = LLVM IR              (source.llvm)
#
# Per-grammar findings from the comparison (rating + how LCC code rendered):
#
#   m68k — OKAY. Some mnemonics are not highlighted (mov, ld, bre ignored;
#     cmp, add are not). Label definitions seem nicely labeled, but label
#     references are ignored. Comments are good.
#
#   gas — BAD. Labels look fine and mnemonics are mostly good, but comments
#     are ignored and inconsistent (highlighting on seemingly random words in
#     a comment line). Label defs are good, label refs ignored. Directives,
#     strings, and numbers are nice; chars are ignored.
#
#   asm — BETTER (chosen). Mnemonics aren't consistently rendered in the same
#     color (mov, cmp, add are good; bre, aout, hout, nl are not). Label defs
#     are highlighted but not differently from the later group of mnemonics
#     and registers. Numbers, chars, and strings are okay.
#
#   LLVM — OK. Label defs look okay, and some mnemonics are highlighted (sub,
#     br, ret) while others are ignored (ldr, str, mov). Comments are good.

# --- global default: asm (Assembly, NASM grammar) for all .a / .ap files ---
*.a   linguist-language=asm
*.a   linguist-detectable=false
*.ap  linguist-language=asm
*.ap  linguist-detectable=false

# --- append-only velocity log: auto-union concurrent appends (#186) ---
# Parallel agents each append a row on close; without this, every `git pull
# --rebase` conflicts on the shared last line. The built-in `union` merge driver
# keeps BOTH sides' added rows automatically (fires under rebase too — verified).
# Rows are unique (ticket + timestamps), so union never drops or dups a row.
# See docs/research/velocity-log-storage.md.
# docs/puzzle-velocity.csv merge=union — REMOVED (#290): CSV is now auto-generated
# by scripts/velocity-export.js (full-file export from ~/.lccjs/velocity.db).
# Two agents exporting the same DB snapshot produce an identical file; no conflict.

# --- append-friendly cluster manifest (#233 prototype; design #222): same rationale ---
# Agents append cluster/blocked_by rows as they group issues; union keeps both sides.
docs/puzzle-clusters.csv merge=union
